# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alex-jesaulenko
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1967-vfl-season] The **1967 VFL season** was the 71st season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1967-vfl-season] The season featured twelve clubs, ran from 15 April until 23 September, and comprised an 18-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top four clubs.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1967-vfl-season] The premiership was won by the Richmond Football Club for the sixth time, after it defeated Geelong by nine points in the 1967 VFL Grand Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1967-vfl-season] In 1967, the VFL competition consisted of twelve teams of 18 on-the-field players each, plus two substitute players, known as the **19th man** and the **20th man**.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1967-vfl-season] A player could be substituted for any reason; however, once substituted, a player could not return to the field of play under any circumstances.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1967-vfl-season] Teams played each other in a home-and-away season of 18 rounds; matches 12 to 18 were the "home-and-way reverse" of matches 1 to 7.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1967-vfl-season] Once the 18 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1967 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the Page–McIntyre system.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1967-vfl-season] The night series were held under the floodlights at Lake Oval, South Melbourne, for the teams (5th to 12th on ladder) out of the finals at the end of the season.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1968-vfl-grand-final] The **1968 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Carlton Football Club and Essendon Football Club, held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground on Saturday, 28 September 1968.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1968-vfl-grand-final] It was the 71st annual Grand Final of the Victorian Football League, staged to determine the premiers for the 1968 VFL season.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1968-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by a record crowd of 116,828 spectators, was won by Carlton by a margin of 3 points, making it that club's ninth premiership victory, but its first since winning the 1947 VFL Grand Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1968-vfl-grand-final] The Blues emerged victorious despite Essendon kicking more goals, the first and only time that had happened in a VFL/AFL grand final until Collingwood defeated Brisbane in the 2023 AFL Grand Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1968-vfl-grand-final] There was a strong wind blowing during the whole game, which did not help it as a spectacle and possibly contributed to Carlton's inaccuracy.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1968-vfl-grand-final] Garry Crane starred on the wing for the Blues with 30 possessions.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1968-vfl-grand-final] Essendon came within a point of Carlton at the 20 minute mark of the final term after a goal to Geoff Blethyn.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1968-vfl-grand-final] Despite being goal-less in the final quarter, Carlton managed to keep their lead, thanks largely to 20th man Neil Chandler, who took some crucial marks in the dying stages.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1968-vfl-grand-final] Aided by the opening during the year of the ground's new Western Stand, the attendance of 116,828 was the highest at a VFL premiership decider up to that time, breaking the record of 115,902 spectators who witnessed the 1956 VFL Grand Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1968-vfl-grand-final] The new record was broken at the 1969 VFL Grand Final, and that record was broken in turn at the 1970 VFL Grand Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] The **All-Australian team** is an all-star team of Australian rules footballers, selected by a panel at the end of each Australian Football League (AFL) season.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] It represents a complete team, including an interchange bench, of the best-performed players during the season, traditionally led by that season's premiership coach.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] The concept of an All-Australian team originated as recognition of performance in interstate football.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] They were named after each Australian National Football Carnival, beginning with the 1953 Adelaide Carnival.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] In the 1980s All-Australian teams were named annually to recognise the best performers in State of Origin series.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] Following the AFL's expansion to a national competition with teams in multiple states, the first AFL All-Australian team was named in 1991.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] Despite the name's implication, the All-Australian team is usually ceremonial in modern times.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] Though the AFL played an All-Star match in 2020, it was the first in 12 years, and the difference in skill level between the All-Australian team and the nearest international competitor is currently too large for any contest to be competitive.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] Despite this, some of these players have represented Australia in AFL Academy junior teams up to the age of 18, as more than two-thirds of all AFL Academy representatives have gone on to play at senior AFL level.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] From 1998 to 2004, the Australian international rules team was mainly composed of All-Australians, and from 2005 to 2013 the team for the annual International Rules Series was selected according to the quite different requirements of International rules football.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] This change was reverted ahead of the 2014 series, with any player who had been selected at least once in *any* All-Australian team being eligible for selection.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] The earliest concept considered to be a precursor to the All-Australian team was an annual team selected by *Sporting Life* magazine between 1947 and 1955.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] A panel of sportswriters at the magazine selected a full team of eighteen from all ANFC-affiliated competitions.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] For a time, AFL historians considered these teams to be official All-Australian teams, but no longer recognises them as such.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] The first official All-Australian team was selected in 1953, immediately after the Australian Football Carnival, which was held in Adelaide on that occasion.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] Based solely upon performances at the carnival, the All-Australian team was selected by representatives of the various state teams.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] This tradition continued at all subsequent interstate carnivals until 1988.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] In 1991, following the VFL's conversion to a national competition and its renaming as the Australian Football League (AFL), an annual All-Australian team based on performances during the AFL premiership season was introduced.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] Since 1999, the All-Australian coach is the coach of the premiership-winning side that year.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] Prior to 2007, only the final selections in the All-Australian team were announced.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] Since 2007, the All-Australian selection committee has nominated the 40 leading players of the year in their playing positions at the conclusion of the home and away season, before announcing the final 22 at a later date during the All-Australian Presentation Dinner.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] The 2023 All-Australian selection panel consists of chairperson Gillon McLachlan, Kevin Bartlett, Eddie Betts, Jude Bolton, Nathan Buckley, Kane Cornes, Andrew Dillon, Glen Jakovich, Laura Kane, Cameron Ling, and Matthew Pavlich.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] In addition to the senior All-Australian team, each year an All-Australian line-up is announced based on the AFL National Under 18 Championships and the AFL National Under 16 Championships.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] The following lists are for senior teams only.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] Members of the All-Australian team are awarded a team blazer, reminiscent of the formal wear traditionally worn by travelling members of national sports teams.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p01] Blazers have become synonymous with the identity of the honour.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p03] The AFL website recognises players who were named in the VFL/AFL Team of the Year from 1982 to 1990 as having All-Australian status.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p03] This was a team picked by Victorian selectors.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p03] Teams were named every season from 1982 to 1990, except 1985.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1969-all-australian-team-p03] These teams were once considered to be equivalent to All-Australian selection, but are no longer recognised as such.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The **1970 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Carlton Football Club and Collingwood Football Club, held at the Melbourne Cricket Ground (MCG) on 26 September 1970.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] It was the 73rd annual Grand Final of the Victorian Football League, staged to determine the premiers for the 1970 VFL season.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The match was won by Carlton who came back from a 44-point deficit at halftime to win by a margin of 10 points, marking that club's 10th premiership victory.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] This game is widely considered to be one of the greatest Grand Finals of all time and, according to one of the key protagonists Ted Hopkins, heralded "the birth of modern football".
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The attendance figure of 121,696 spectators broke the grand final record set the previous year of 119,165 spectators, and set an all-time attendance record for any football code in Australia that still stands.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood finished 1970 on top of the ladder with 18 wins.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Carlton was next with 16 wins, followed by St Kilda and South Melbourne (14 wins each).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] South Melbourne was participating in its first Finals series since 1945, and got in despite winning only four of their last eight home-and-away matches.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] During the home-and-away season, Collingwood and Carlton had played each other twice.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] In Round 8 at VFL Park, Carlton had led by 29 points at half-time before being overrun to lose by 23.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the return fixture at Victoria Park in Round 19, Collingwood thrashed Carlton by 77 points, at the time the club's greatest winning margin against Carlton.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The two clubs faced each other again in the Second Semi-final, which was a closely fought battle won by Collingwood 17.16 (118) d.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Carlton qualified for the grand final with a comfortable 62-point victory against St Kilda in the preliminary final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood had last played in a VFL Grand Final in 1966, which was won by St Kilda by one point, while the Blues were playing in their third consecutive VFL Grand Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The match was the fourth grand final between the two traditional rivals, the previous occurring in 1910, 1915 and 1938.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Percy Beames, chief football writer for *The Age*, predicted a Collingwood win, along with four other colleagues, while three tipped a Carlton premiership, among them Geelong full-forward Doug Wade.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood named an unchanged line-up from the team that had defeated Carlton in the Second Semi-final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] There had been some concern over star ruckman Len Thompson, who had not trained for the entire week leading up to the Grand Final on doctor's orders.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The umpiring panel for the match, comprising one field umpire, two boundary umpires and two goal umpires is given below.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The attendance of 121,696 spectators was the highest in the history of the league, a record still held today.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Carlton captain Nicholls won the toss and chose to kick toward the Punt Road End.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Kicking against a very slight breeze, Collingwood were into attack straight away when umpire Jolley awarded a free kick to ruckman Jenkin from the opening bounce.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] For the next 20 minutes, the Magpies midfielders continually won the ball and drove deep into the forward line with long kicks, while the Blues struggled to maintain any sort of meaningful possession.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood opened the scoring with behinds before former captain Tuddenham gathered the ball from a handpass under pressure from Max Richardson, evaded an attempted bump and snapped the first goal of the game at the 5-minute mark.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Star full-forward McKenna followed up with his first goal of the match at the 13-minute mark, converting a free kick set shot after great play upfield from O'Callaghan, Price and Tuddenham.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] After his snap shot hit the post earlier in the quarter, Britt received a handball from McKenna in the forward pocket to score Collingwood's third goal at the 23-minute mark.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Up to that stage, Carlton had yet to register a score, but the Magpies had not fully capitalized on their momentum, with their score only reading 3 goals 6 behinds (24 points).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] It took the Blues until the 23-minute mark of the quarter to register its first score, with a behind to Crosswell after bringing the ball forward through scrappy play.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] A minute later, Jesaulenko had a great chance to kick Carlton's first goal when he took a strong mark from a rushed kick forward by Silvagni, only to miss his set shot from directly in front.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood responded at the 29-minute mark when a pass from Wayne Richardson found McKenna, whose set shot from 20 yards out on a slight angle gave him his second goal for the game.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The quarter-time siren sounded shortly afterward, with Collingwood 29 points ahead.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The Blues finally scored their first goal of the game in the second minute of the quarter, when rover Gallagher converted his free kick set shot after a careless bump from Jenkin.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood responded almost immediately when McKenna got front position to a long kick into the forward line from Dean and marked strongly before kicking his third goal.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Then at the 8-minute mark, the Magpies scored two goals in quick succession; the first came when Clifton intercepted an attempted pass by Gallagher on Carlton's half-forward line and kicked long into attack.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Coming out from Collingwood's forward line to gather possession of the ball, Dunne grabbed it on the half volley, turned on to his non-preferred left foot and snapped a long-range goal.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Then from the subsequent centre bounce, Collingwood captain Waters sharked Jones' hit-out and sent another long kick into Collingwood's forward line.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] McKenna was in the right place to gather the bouncing ball and snap his fourth goal to extend Collingwood's lead to 44 points.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] As such, the half time margin remained 44 points.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Notable among the highlights in the quarter came in the 27th minute, when Jesaulenko (Carlton) leapt onto the shoulders of Collingwood ruckman Graeme Jenkin and took a spectacular mark that was judged the official 1970 Mark of the Year.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Mike Williamson's TV commentary of the mark, "Oh, Jesaulenko, you beauty!" has endured as famous as the mark itself, and was later included in the Toyota Legendary Moments series of advertisements.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Although the Magpies had built a formidable and seemingly insurmountable half-time lead, there was one incident that had fans worried; Collingwood's superstar full-forward McKenna was groggy after teammate Tuddenham had accidentally floored him with a hip-and-shoulder while flying for a chest mark.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] McKenna, who already had kicked over 140 goals for the season and five goals in the first half.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] He would only kick one more goal for the rest of the match.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The fact that this goal came from an overhead mark only 2 minutes and 43 seconds after the collision caused the TV commentators to believe that he had recovered.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] During the break, champion Carlton coach Ron Barassi instructed his players to handball and play on at all costs, instituting a strategy to try to nullify Collingwood's long kicking game.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] A key positional move was the introduction of little-known Ted Hopkins, a small rover, as a substitute for Bert Thornley in the second half.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] These changes were highly effective and in the early part of the third quarter, Carlton staged one of the most remarkable purple patches in league history, kicking seven goals in eleven minutes to draw the margin back to only three points.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Substitute Ted Hopkins kicked the first two, roving the ball from broken marking contests in the goal square in the 3rd and 4th minutes of the quarter.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the 7th minute, Syd Jackson snapped a goal from near the boundary line in the forward pocket.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the 8th minute, Brent Crosswell kicked a goal from a high tackle free kick.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Hopkins kicked his third goal in the 10th minute after receiving a handpass from Robert Walls, who had marked at half-forward; and in the 12th minute, Walls marked at half forward again, this time playing on and kicking the goal himself.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Finally, in the 14th minute, from a ball-up in the forward pocket, Hopkins managed to kick the ball to Alex Jesaulenko who scored a goal to bring the margin back to only three points, 10.14 (74) vs 11.5 (71).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Thereafter, Collingwood steadied, and the second half of the third quarter was a much more even contest.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the 20th minute, Collingwood extended the lead to 10 points with a set shot goal by Len Thompson.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Two minutes later, Jesaulenko kicked a goal for Carlton from a free kick, and from the ensuing centre bounce, Collingwood responded with a goal to Ross Dunne from a close range mark.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the 28th minute, McKenna marked and kicked his sixth goal from 20m, and shortly before the three-quarter time siren he kicked another behind, to extend the margin to 17 points.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] At this point, Collingwood was 21 points ahead, having scored the last three goals.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Soon after, Carlton had three shots inside three minutes to narrow the margin back to eight points, largely through the efforts of ruckman John Nicholls who was resting forward.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] No goals were kicked in the following ten minutes, both teams' defences repeatedly repelling attacks.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Collingwood's 19th and 20th men were both brought on to replace cramping teammates.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] In the 20th minute, Syd Jackson made a brilliant piece of individual play, smothering then regathering an attempted clearing kick by Eakins, before handpassing to an unmarked Hopkins at full forward, who kicked his fourth goal and brought the margin back to one point.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] As time-on neared, Crosswell was awarded a free kick for a high tackle from Tuddenham and took his set shot on an angle from 35 metres out.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] In an interview for the *AFL Record* 50 years later, Crosswell recalled that “the wind was going slightly right to left and I remember thinking I needed to kick it towards the right goalpost.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The Blues had taken the lead for the first time in the match, amidst scenes of pandemonium in the stands.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] At this point, Carlton had kicked the last 5.2 (32) of the game.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Dunne kicked a behind for Collingwood in the 29th minute to narrow the margin to ten points, and the siren went shortly after.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] This was the same winning margin as the Second Semi Final also played at the MCG two weeks earlier between these teams which Collingwood won 17.16 (118) to 17.6 (108).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Leading ball winners for Carlton were Crosswell with 23 (17 kicks and 6 handballs), McKay 20 (18 and 2) and Waite 19 (10 and 9).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] For Collingwood, Price 22 (17 and 5), W.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Richardson 19 (13 and 6) Brent Crosswell (Carlton) was generally regarded as the best player on the day for his four-quarter contribution, especially in the first half when many Carlton players were not playing well.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Hopkins, whose four goals as 19th man became legendary, played only one further game for Carlton, soon quitting football to pursue other interests.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The game was immediately hailed across the Australian sporting press as an all-time classic.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] He also wrote that the Collingwood players had little excuse for letting down their coach Bob Rose, compared to their losses in 1964 and 1966.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Besides their scoring inaccuracy, Beames also criticised Collingwood for their lack of heart and ability to rise to the challenge in the final quarter, as well as focusing too much on their spearhead McKenna, while citing Carlton's evenness as the key to victory.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The 44-point half-time deficit overcome by Carlton was then the second-largest half-time deficit ever overcome in VFL history.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The only larger deficit overcome before this was 52 points, by Collingwood against St Kilda in Round 10 earlier in the season (which remains the record as of 2025).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] , speaking to a radio interview after the game.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] The game, and Barassi's half time instructions, are sometimes referred to as "the birth of modern football", a label which critical historical analysis views as symbolic, rather than literal.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Carlton's recovery in the 1970 grand final symbolized this transition perfectly: falling 44 points behind in the first half playing "old football", then recovering to win playing "new football" in the second half.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Nevertheless, the mythology surrounding the game has perpetuated a myth that Barassi's half-time instructions represented a revolutionary, seminal moment which heralded the transition from the old style of football to the modern style.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] This literal interpretation does not hold up to any critical assessment: Barassi noted that Carlton had been playing a handball style of game throughout 1970, and credited early 1960s Fitzroy coach Len Smith as being the first coach to encourage attacking use of handball in Victoria.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Football historian John Devaney assessed likewise that the transition towards handball and playing on had been gradual through the 1960s, and was already a well established tactic both within and outside Victoria in the years before 1970.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Barassi and Devaney both also note that Carlton's recovery couldn't be attributed to handball alone, with Hopkins strong play, better overall discipline and winning a higher proportion of possession also key to the recovery.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1970-vfl-grand-final] Sports journalist Jake Niall, writing in 2020 as *The Age'*s chief football writer, argued that the 1970 Grand Final was "the most consequential match in the history of Australian rules football, the game that mattered most".
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] The **1972 VFL Grand Final** was an Australian rules football game contested between the Richmond Football Club and Carlton Football Club at the Melbourne Cricket Ground on 7 October 1972.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] It was the 75th annual Grand Final of the Victorian Football League, staged to determine the premiers for the 1972 VFL season.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] The match, attended by 112,393 spectators, was won by Carlton by a margin of 27 points, marking that club's 11th premiership victory.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] At the conclusion of the regular home-and-away season, Carlton had finished first on the ladder with 18 wins, 3 losses and a draw.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Richmond had finished second with 18 wins and 4 losses.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] In the finals series leading up to the Grand Final, Richmond defeated Collingwood by 44 points in the Qualifying Final before meeting Carlton in the Second Semi Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] This game resulted in a draw, with both teams scoring 8.13 (61).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] In the Second Semi Final Replay, Richmond won comfortably by 41 points, sending them straight through to the Grand Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Carlton then beat St Kilda by 16 points to match up with Richmond once again in the premiership decider.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Richmond went into the Grand Final as the clear favourites.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Even though Carlton finished on top of the ladder, they had lost twice to Richmond during the regular season, and then were thrashed in the Second Semi Final replay.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] The statistics lent further weight to Richmond's favouritism; Carlton had not beaten the Tigers in a final since 1920.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] The 1972 Grand Final was played under dull skies but on a superb MCG surface.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Carlton made eight positional changes to its team, the most notable was that of captain-coach John Nicholls, who put himself in the forward pocket, and gave first ruck responsibilities to Peter "Percy" Jones.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Less than two minutes into the game, Trevor Keogh opened the scoring for Carlton before goals to Barry Richardson and Neil Balme put Richmond in front.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] But then Carlton kicked the next four goals – two of them to Nicholls – and would never again relinquish the lead.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] At quarter time, Carlton led by 18 points, having kicked 8.4 (52), a record first-quarter score for a Grand Final, to 5.4 (34).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Some thirteen goals had been scored, and it wouldn't end there.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] As well as Carlton had played in the first quarter, they were even better in the second.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Although Kevin Morris opened the scoring within 30 seconds to cut the margin to 12 points, the Blues responded by kicking four goals in four minutes.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] By the 23-minute mark of the quarter, the Blues had kicked eight goals to reach 100 points.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Richmond had still managed to score five goals for the quarter, but Carlton were unstoppable, kicking a record ten goals for the quarter.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] The only worry was on the injury front; David McKay had had his jaw broken in two places by Balme, and Vin Waite had been stretchered off with a broken ankle.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] And when Syd Jackson kicked truly at the 30-minute mark of the third quarter, the Blues had broken the record for the highest score in a Grand Final with still over a quarter to play.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Exactly 50 goals were kicked in the game, with the teams compiling a combined score of 50.27 (327).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] This was, at the time, the highest scoring game in VFL history, Grand Final or otherwise, and has been bettered only seven times since.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Carlton's score of 28.9 (177) remains the highest in Grand Final history, and Richmond's 22.18 (150) remains the highest losing score in a Grand Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Richmond's score was the tenth highest score of the season: only in 1924, 1937, 1940, 1954, 1962, 1976 and 2001 have other teams lost matches with scores among the ten highest of a season.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Carlton vice-captain Robert Walls was unanimously rated best on ground, kicking six goals and directly assisting in seven others.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Ruckman Peter "Percy" Jones played arguably his finest game for Carlton, while Alex Jesaulenko kicked seven goals and John Nicholls bagged six.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Richmond had eleven individual goal-kickers, with Neil Balme kicking five.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Carlton's opening term score of 8.4 (52) and second term score of 10.2 (62) set the records for the best first and second quarter scores in Grand Final history (Hawthorn would later equal the first quarter score in the 1989 VFL Grand Final).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] The 1972 premiership victory was John Nicholls' finest moment, cementing his place in football history as one of the great strategists.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] After being mocked by opponents and berated by critics following Carlton's thrashing in the Second Semi Final, Nicholls knew that the only way to beat Richmond was to outscore them.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] In another tactical move, Nicholls decided not to implement the planned game changes in the Preliminary final against St Kilda, thus keeping Richmond in the dark about his intentions.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Instead, he trusted his players to beat the Saints playing their orthodox game, and also credited his senior players for understanding and executing the plan.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] On the day Nicholls launched the plan by loading the forward line with his best players and instructing the team to play a fast, direct game that would not allow Richmond to settle.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Nicholls was also aware that in the 25 games that both Richmond and Carlton had played in 1972 leading up to the Grand Final, Richmond had conceded nearly 500 more points than Carlton.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] The unsuspecting Tigers fielded the same six defenders that had held Carlton to nine goals in the Second Semi Final replay two weeks earlier.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Nicholls put himself in the forward pocket against Ray Boyanich and made him pay for loose play by kicking six goals, three of them in the first quarter.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Afterwards Nicholls said it was the easiest physical game he had played in.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Full-back Dick Clay described the loss as "surreal", Francis Bourke as "almost eerie".
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] If this was Nicholls' finest moment, it was also the worst day of Richmond coach Tom Hafey's career.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] Several days after the match, chief football writer for *The Age* Percy Beames wrote that losing the Semi Final replay was the best thing that could have happened to Carlton.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] This was the first of two consecutive Grand Finals to be contested between these teams.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1972-vfl-grand-final] In the 1973 VFL Grand Final the fortunes were reversed, with Richmond running out winners by a margin of 30 points.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1976-vfl-season] The **1976 VFL season** was the 80th season of the Victorian Football League (VFL), the highest level senior Australian rules football competition in Victoria.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1976-vfl-season] The season featured twelve clubs, ran from 3 April until 25 September, and comprised a 22-game home-and-away season followed by a finals series featuring the top five clubs.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1976-vfl-season] The premiership was won by the Hawthorn Football Club for the third time, after it defeated North Melbourne by 30 points in the 1976 VFL Grand Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1976-vfl-season] In 1976, the VFL competition consisted of twelve teams of 18 on-the-field players each, plus two substitute players, known as the **19th man** and the **20th man**.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1976-vfl-season] Teams played each other in a home-and-away season of 22 rounds; matches 12 to 22 were the "home-and-away reverse" of matches 1 to 11 (except that rounds 14 and 15 were the reverse of 4 and 3 respectively).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/1976-vfl-season] Once the 22 round home-and-away season had finished, the 1976 VFL *Premiers* were determined by the specific format and conventions of the "McIntyre final five system".
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko is a Legend of the Australian Football Hall of Fame, and as a player was known for his versatility, uncanny balance and spectacular marking.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He immortalised his reputation in the game by taking the most iconic mark in football history in the 1970 VFL Grand Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In 2009 *The Australian* nominated Jesaulenko as one of the 25 greatest footballers never to win a Brownlow Medal.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Recruited from Canberra, Jesaulenko has played more games and kicked more goals than any other player from the Australian Capital Territory.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He represented his home territory in 1978.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] His popularity caused the code to surge in popularity there, and he remains a household name in the ACT.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He remains to date the only Carlton footballer to have kicked 100 or more goals in a season, and the last player-coach to win a VFL/AFL premiership (1979).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In 2002, he was inducted into the Ukrainian Sports Hall of Fame.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] On 20 October 2010, he was inducted into the Sport Australia Hall of Fame.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In July 2013, Jesaulenko was named captain of the first Australia Post Multicultural Team of Champions.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In January 2022, Jesaulenko was diagnosed with Parkinson's disease.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko was born in Salzburg, then Allied-occupied Austria.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] His father, Vasil, was Ukrainian and served as a German policeman during World War II.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] His mother, Vera, was born in Russia, and she had survived the horrors of seeing her father shot dead by German soldiers and having her first child, whom she first gave the name Alex, taken away from her when she was in a German prison camp.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] The child was not heard of again until over fifty years later.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Along with many other Eastern Europeans who were World War II refugees or displaced persons, the Jesaulenkos emigrated to Australia via the Norwegian passenger ship *SS Skaugum*.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] They arrived in the port of Melbourne on 28 July 1949.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] They spent the first six months living at the Bonegilla Migrant Reception and Training Centre.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] According to Jesaulenko, the family name should have been spelt *Esaulenko*, but immigration officials listed "Esaulenko" with a "J" in front, thinking that they had heard a "J" in his name.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] From there, the family moved to Canberra, where Vasil set up shop as a carpenter-cabinetmaker.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] The young Jesaulenko was enrolled at St Edmund's College and then Telopea Park High, where he played soccer and rugby union.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He did not start playing Australian rules football until he was 14 years old.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He began playing at the Eastlake Football Club in Canberra.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko has credited his time at Eastlake for instilling in him a winning culture.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] After breaking into the senior team, he quickly established himself as a star, playing in three consecutive premierships for Eastlake from 1964 to 1966.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko made his senior VFL debut in the opening round of the 1967 season against Fitzroy at Princes Park, where he had 14 touches and kicked two goals in a 94-point victory.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He would play every game for Carlton that season, one of four players to do so.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In that season's Brownlow Medal count, he would poll 15 votes to finish third behind eventual winner Ross Smith (24 votes) from St Kilda and North Melbourne's Laurie Dwyer (17 votes).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko would go on to play in four Carlton premierships – in 1968, 1970, 1972 and 1979.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko was selected for All-Australian honours in 1969 and 1972.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He also has the dubious record at Carlton for the most inaccurate score of 5 goals and 12 behinds, against Hawthorn in 1969.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In December 1969, Jesaulenko put an end to newspaper rumours that he might leave Carlton and either play football in Western Australia or return to Canberra.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] It was well known that he was working as a barman at a Melbourne hotel at the time, and was receiving little more than the "average" player.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] A spectacular and popular player, Jesaulenko was renowned for his high marking, mercurial ground play, superb balance and goalkicking.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He kicked 115 goals in the 1970 season, breaking the club record and becoming the first (and, as of 2021, only) player to kick more than 100 goals in a season for Carlton.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He went on to play in the famous 1970 VFL Grand Final against Collingwood.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In front of an all-time record MCG crowd of 121,696 fans, Carlton came from a 44-point deficit at half-time to win by 10 points.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko's marking skill was perhaps best highlighted by a spectacular mark over big Collingwood ruckman Graeme Jenkin in the 1970 VFL Grand Final.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] The commentary has Mike Williamson shouting the now-famous phrase: *"Oh, Jesaulenko, you beauty!"*.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] This "specky" is acclaimed by some to be the "Mark of the Century", and it was the first to be recognised officially as the Mark of the Year; the medal awarded to the annual winner is called the Alex Jesaulenko Medal.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko has downplayed the specky, citing other marks he took—even during the same game—as greater feats.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He later said: "The images make it look classical, like it was taken from the marking manual, ...
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] For a brief period in 1977, Jesaulenko wrote a weekly Tuesday column for *The Canberra Times* called 'Jezza on Rules'.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko's vision would be realised 13 years later when the VFL became the Australian Football League.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] The 1978 VFL season began dreadfully for Carlton.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] After finishing top of the ladder in 1976 but losing the Preliminary Final by one point and then losing in the last round of the home-and-away season to miss out on the finals in 1977, they had brought Ian Stewart over from South Melbourne to replace Ian Thorogood as senior coach.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] By Round 6, they had only won one game and were sitting second-last on the ladder, and Stewart had gone.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Carlton president George Harris turned to Sergio Silvagni to fill the void while a long-term replacement was being sought, but on the suggestion of media personality Michael Williamson, Harris gave the job to Jesaulenko.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko's sporting achievements were recognised outside the football world as well; he was included in the 1979 New Year Honours list as a Member (Civil) of the Order of the British Empire "for service to the sport of Australian Rules football".
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko continued on as Carlton's captain-coach in 1979.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] With a superb support cast, the Blues took out the minor premiership with 19 wins and also set a new VFL record for the largest-scoring aggregate in a home-and-away season (2,772 points).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In the second quarter of the Round 10 match against Collingwood at Princes Park, Jesaulenko was running back with the flight of the ball when he was met heavily by Stan Magro, resulting in concussion and a shoulder injury.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] The Blues were trailing by 25 points at that stage, but they rallied and fought back with a strong second half to win by 16 points.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Amazingly, Jesaulenko was back in action just two weeks later in the Round 12 game against Geelong at Kardinia Park; trailing by 30 points at the last change, Carlton almost pulled off a great comeback, eventually falling short by six points.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] After the 43-point win against Essendon in Round 15 at Princes Park, in which he had 22 touches and kicked a goal, Jesaulenko missed the next six games with what was later revealed to be a back injury; he had suffered damage to his sciatic nerve which had caused him to lose feeling in his right leg.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He underwent a daily 30-minute exercise routine to strengthen his stomach and back muscles, returning to on-field action in time for the final round of the home-and-away season against South Melbourne at Princes Park.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko was, in fact, the last player-coach in the VFL/AFL to win a premiership, and he is likely to remain so indefinitely.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko had pay disputes with Carlton in 1977.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Subsequently, he tied his ongoing presence at the club to then-Carlton club president George Harris.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] At the end of the 1979 season, despite the premiership, Harris was ousted from his position as President of Carlton Football Club, and Jesaulenko walked out on Carlton and resigned from the club.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In a deal managed by trucking multimillionaire (now billionaire) and St Kilda club president Lindsay Fox, Jesaulenko moved to the St Kilda Football Club in 1980.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] While initially appointed as an on-field player only, Jesaulenko was then appointed playing coach when the incumbent St Kilda senior coach, Mike Patterson, was sacked by Fox after Round 2.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He played 23 games and kicked 20 goals for the Saints in 1980–1981 and stayed on for a further season as senior coach.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko retired as a player after Round 8 on 16 May 1981.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He was the last person to serve as captain-coach in the VFL; however, Malcolm Blight was a player-coach at North Melbourne until Round 16 of the same season but was not captain during this time.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] After leaving St Kilda, Jesaulenko went north to serve as captain-coach of Sandgate in the then-Queensland Football League.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He retired at the end of 1984 after Sandgate lost their semi-final, after which he moved into the hotel business in Queensland for several years.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In the first half of the 1989 VFL season, Carlton was in disarray when communication had almost completely broken down between the players and senior coach Robert Walls, who only two seasons prior had guided the Blues to the flag.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Carlton had fallen one game short of the Grand Final in 1988 but started the 1989 season with five straight losses.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] The defining point came after losing to the Brisbane Bears by three points in Round 10 at home, with Warwick Capper kicking the winning goal after the siren.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] At that stage, the Blues were second-last on the ladder with only two wins and in danger of "winning" their first-ever wooden spoon.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Walls was sacked as Carlton Football Club senior coach two days after the match.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko had not been back at Carlton since his acrimonious departure almost a decade earlier, when he was appointed caretaker senior coach of Carlton for the remainder of the 1989 season.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko's optimism appeared to rub off on the Carlton players; they beat Sydney by 28 points and would win six more games to finish eighth.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko stepped down as Carlton Football Club senior coach at the end of the 1990 season and was replaced by David Parkin, who returned in his second stint as Carlton senior coach.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] His last coaching appointment, at Coburg for the 1993 season, was a total disaster, with the Lions losing all eighteen games during a losing sequence of thirty games in the dying days of the Victorian Football Association.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] When Carlton set up their Hall of Fame in 1987, Jesaulenko was one of the inaugural inductees.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] He was also an inaugural inductee into the Australian Football Hall of Fame in 1996, and in 2008 was elevated to Legend status.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In 1996, he was also named on the half-forward flank in the AFL Team of the Century.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In 1997, he was inducted as an official Legend of the Carlton Football Club.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] When the Carlton Team of the Century was announced, Jesaulenko was also named on the half-forward flank.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Upon being elevated to Legend status in the Australian Football Hall of Fame, Jesaulenko was accorded tribute from the great contemporaries of his era.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] After retiring from football, Jesaulenko worked for billionaire and noted Carlton patron Richard Pratt at his recycling firm Visy for 15 years in the sales and public relations department.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] When it was known that Pratt was in his last days in April 2009, Jesaulenko contemplated paying him a farewell visit at his mansion, but thought better of it lest he attracted too much attention.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] During the 1970s, when people spoke about football, it was common for people to refer to taking a high mark as "taking a Jezza".
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Be in it.* advertisement, the character "Norm" says "Beauty, Jezza" while watching football.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] Jesaulenko is mentioned in the 1985 song "The Back Upon Which Jezza Jumped" by Melbourne band TISM (This Is Serious, Mum), appearing on the band's self-titled demo tape.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] The song depicts Graeme "Jerker" Jenkin being left to be forgotten because of Jezza's spectacular mark.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] The main character in the Australian children's book *Jezza* is a dog named after Alex Jesaulenko.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] "Ordinary dogs chase tennis balls or fetch silly sticks.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] My new family called me Jezza because that was the name of a famous footballer.
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] I don't mean to brag, but I'm quite a footballer too." (Bell, 1991).
[src:alex-jesaulenko/alex-jesaulenko] In 2012, singer-songwriter Tex Perkins wrote and performed "Jesaulenko You Beauty" exclusively for *The Marngrook Footy Show*.
